{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641741"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:31:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:31:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17903"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17903"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.28,0.14,0,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109888"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10617"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92249"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"10049"},{"type":"tags","id":"10052"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24808"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109888"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are several gut hormones that can trigger the sensation of satiety. One of these, in particular, is released by gut mucosal enteroendocrine cells where it induces acute cessation of feeding, inhibits gastric emptying, stimulates pancreatic enzyme secretion and promotes intestinal motility. This hormone acts on specific gut receptors, with the signal transmitted to brainstem nuclei through afferent vagal fibres.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following has these characteristics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peptide YY","Ghrelin","Glucagon-like peptide-1","Insulin","Cholecystokinin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholecystokinin (CCK)\u003C/strong\u003E is a hormone released by enteroendocrine cells in the gut in response to food intake. It plays a crucial role in inducing satiety by inhibiting gastric emptying and stimulating pancreatic enzyme secretion. CCK acts on specific receptors in the gut, and the signal is transmitted to the brainstem via afferent vagal nerves, contributing to the sensation of fullness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptide YY\u003C/strong\u003E is another gut hormone involved in satiety, but it primarily acts by slowing gastric motility and reducing appetite after meals. It does not have the same direct effects on pancreatic enzyme secretion as CCK.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1)\u003C/strong\u003E is also involved in satiety and glucose metabolism, but its primary actions include enhancing insulin secretion and inhibiting glucagon release. It does not directly stimulate pancreatic enzyme secretion like CCK.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin\u003C/strong\u003E is a hormone primarily involved in glucose metabolism and does not have the same direct effects on gastric emptying or pancreatic enzyme secretion as CCK.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGhrelin\u003C/strong\u003E is a hormone that stimulates appetite, not satiety. It is released primarily from the stomach and signals hunger to the brain, which is the opposite of the satiety-inducing effects of CCK.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cholecystokinin (CCK) is released in response to food intake and plays a role in satiety by inhibiting gastric emptying and stimulating pancreatic enzyme secretion.","CCK acts on specific receptors in the gut, with signals transmitted to the brainstem via afferent vagal nerves."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020 Oct 8;64(4):607-647. doi: 10.1042/EBC20190041. PMID: 32830223; PMCID: PMC7545035","Austin J, Marks D. Hormonal regulators of appetite. Int J Pediatr Endocrinol. 2009;2009:141753. doi: 10.1155/2009/141753. Epub 2008 Dec 3. PMID: 19946401; PMCID: PMC2777281","Hernando-Redondo J, Toloba A, Benaiges D, Salas-Salvad\u00f3 J, Mart\u00ednez-Gonzalez MA, Corella D, Estruch R, Tinahones FJ, Ros E, Goday A, Casta\u00f1er O, Fit\u00f3 M. Mid- and long-term changes in satiety-related hormones, lipid and glucose metabolism, and inflammation after a Mediterranean diet intervention with the goal of losing weight: A randomized, clinical trial. Front Nutr. 2022 Nov 18;9:950900. doi: 10.3389/fnut.2022.950900. PMID: 36466401; PMCID: PMC9716624","Yeung AY, Tadi P. Physiology, Obesity Neurohormonal Appetite And Satiety Control. 2023 Jan 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310366"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92249"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17903"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92249"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T13:59:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T13:59:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10617"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109888"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.em